title: Grateful Dead Live at Town Park on 1987-08-16
lineage: Cassette Master (Tascam 122mkII) -> Apogee MiniMe (24bit/48k) -> Samplitude Professional v8.01 -> FLAC/16
description:
Set 1

Mississippi Half-Step Uptown Toodeloo  ->
Little Red Rooster  
Iko Iko

Set 2

reviews.review_text:
waste of time this show sucked from start to finish.

Great weekend! but Sunday the Band was tired and so was the crowd.

The Harmonic Convergence was a great experience at Sunrise.

Musically the whole week was lacking except for a few moments here and there. I would say it was one of those moments the Boys failed to grasp once again.

But thanks to Bobo for bringing the Boys to the Box Canyon.

WHAT PLANET ARE YOU ON?! This show was GREAT!  Listen again.  C. Miller wouldn't have focused on THIS show if it totally sucked.  You don't see a Miller recording of that shitty show in 84' (can't remember the name)

Or MOST of the pre-coma shows, do you?

Start at West LA Fadeaway and go from there!
8-16-87 Good show. Nice matrix remaster by Charlie. I know these reviews are subjective but don't listen to negative people who hand out two stars.
Charlie Miller is King!!! Thanks Charlie for doing all you do......

Give me a Break I couldnt let "JerryinaPuch";s xcomments go unheeded - 

Do you REALLy think most opre-coma shows sucked? If so you were either a) not on tour, or b) highly inexperienced regarding the Dead, or c) on dope.

The shows I saw pre-Coma BLOW AWAY the shows I saw after summer '86.  First of all take away post-90, once Brent was gone they never found it again.  The late '80's shows were ncie and clean sometimes, tight band, but zero chances, zero jams.  even the one tour fall '89 - those "jams" were so short.  A Playin from '81 or '83 or even '84 blows that away.  The Dead also had a much more powerful sound pre-coma, plus they were flat-out younger. The original Modulus 6-string bass Phil played from '83-'86 and Brent on teh Hammond B-3 was some serious power.  They lost that during the "Touch head" era.

I was at these shows, no great shakes.  band was fine, spectacular venue, Greeks '85 made these shows look like Duran Duran. Wwell maybe now I'm over exagerrating.. Actually all of '85 does.  The Spectrum Big Boss had so much more energy and spunk, the band was almosttame in the late - '80's.  I like em rough and raunchy, mot midi'd.

Moronic Convergence It's hard to believe that there were people in the late 20th century who actually believed that the alignment of the planets would herald a new age of peace, but the party surrounding it sure was a lot of fun.  This is a good solid show from the Dead's post-coma renaissance period.  The comments after the snafu and re-start of Brokedown Palace are hilarious.

YAWNN..If you get confused..Listen to the music play What a beautiful place to see the Grateful Dead.. I'm going to keep this short and sweet..TeaBag69 you bore the hell out of me and I'm giving this show 4 stars because you gave it 3 stars..stop hating and being negative..life is way to short? Forever Grateful>Forever Dead!!! Give this a whirl if you love music..@! Searching for the Sound...all of it @!@!@! Sink like a Stone>Float like a Feather

Mid to good show, but tracks are off This is one of those recordings where the encores are smushed onto the end of the first set, which throws the whole track listing out of whack. Just beware, if you like to listen to a show in order, that When Push Comes to Shove starts set two and follows Promised Land. If you hear Touch of Grey, you've gone too far!
